Object Description: My group created two wooden pieces to be used as enrichment for the birds in the Jacksonville Zoo's River Valley Aviary, specifically the macaws. Our first object constructed was a wooden food puzzle inspired by an abacus. The object has bamboo bars with holes for food, and wooden rings that can be moved to reveal the food. This object was designed to offer a puzzle and a reward for food acquisition, specifically for the macaws. The second object build was a wooden perch with a block chain toy. The purpose of this object was to create a place where birds could perch, maintain their beaks, and widen their choices of areas they can be. The macaw object was placed near their enclosure, and the "treehouse sanctuary" was placed high in a separate tree.
Challenging Part: The beginning was the most challenging because we had trouble narrowing down ideas and combining elements that we preferred. I think my group spent a little longer idea ideating than other groups, and at times it was difficult to maintain focus. It is easiest to create something when you are excited and passionate about it.
Successful Part: The most successful part of the design process for my group was construction. Typically in group work, production among members is variable. However, both my group members worked hard every day, and were happy to take on any task.
Other Useful Info: More information from the zoo about bird species, size, behavior, and common areas of habitation.
Any Problems: Someone came in to work independently once and did a task out of order, but we were able to solve the issue.
Improvements: Begin every day with a plan of action, and what you would like to complete. Note how many people are needed for each task and delegate. Make sure all the tools and equipment needed is present.
Advice: If you start to feel lost, ground yourself in useful and necessary information.

Object Description: Our enrichment item was a pyramidal like structure with a rope mechanism on top that encourages the komodo dragon to use its strength when feeding.  This is encouraged by the food at the top of the structure being attached to a rope with a counterweight, so the komodo will have to ascend the structure, grab the food, and pull against this weight by using its muscles and securing itself on the structure.
Challenging Part: Fabrication of our enrichment item was very difficult considering its size.  Trying to make an item that was large forced us to consider the convenience of transportation and effective use of materials to reduce the cost.
Successful Part: Creating a model and visualizing how our enrichment item was very helpful as it determined which goals were achievable and provided a rough idea of how we would construct such an item.
Any Problems: Having to create many components by hand instead of buying ones already made was very challenging and added a lot of time to our construction process.  However, this was a valuable lesson in learning how these things are made and better enlighten us on effectively using our time and how to streamline construction processes.
Improvements: I think having more strict deadlines would make the process more demanding, however it would certainly help keep all groups at an equal pace and discourage these projects being done last minute.
Advice: "Plan until you can't plan anymore", many parts of our project involved figuring things out as we were mid-fabrication, so being prepared for these changes beforehand instead of having to do so in a later stage makes the project a lot less complicated and minimizes extra time spent on it.
Feedback: With the scale of our project, maybe having another group member on top of the four that we were could have been helpful.  We were really working on one component at a time when fabricating this object, so maybe considering more group members when understanding the scale of the project could have been helpful.

Object Description: Puzzle feeder/ Foraging log for beak maintenance, increasing feed time and cognitive enrichment
Challenging Part: The transition between prototype to model, our group had to make a lot of modifications due to materials and time limitations.
Successful Part: The ideation gave us a really good framework to work with by helping us stay on track and knowing what to prioritize when completing the project and for what reason each of the elements our project were there.
Any Problems: Mostly time constraints, we underestimated how much time it would take to comeplete one of our logs and we wanted to do two and wanted to add a lot more surfacing but the actual construction took longer so we had little time for aesthetics
Improvements: I think my group was excited about working on the prototype since it turned out great. And cut our time down for construction. I think in general the process was great but maybe more guided group check ins to show what we had and talk out loud about the next steps to be able to stay on track and manage our time better.
Advice: This is for me personally but I would have liked to assert myself a little more. At times I felt like I was at disadvantage because I hadn’t taken a sculpture class in a really long time, so I was afraid of giving my opinion too much and wasting people’s time. So for the future I would say to be sure of myself and my ideas because they are just as valuable. For the group I would say to focus on time management and take risks. I would say that we started doing a lot of experiments because we were afraid to waste our materials because they were limited at the beginning.
Feedback: This class was an amazing and fulfilling class to go through the process in general. At the beginning, if I remember correctly the ideation of projects was handed out at random, I think that if we had chosen the animals more passionate ideas could have come out. Either way, it was a long process between ideation and realistic sketching so I don’t know that it really made a difference.

Object Description: Abacus inspired feeder to for lengthen and feed time and exerting effort. Multi-species perch for interspecies interaction, play, feeding, and beak maintenance.
Challenging Part: tThe model making phase felt difficult because it was hard to image how the object was going to exist in the real world, be used by the animals, and fabricated with materials.
Successful Part: Revisions after receiving zoo feedback. This narrowed down what we needed to get done rather than focusing on the big picture or small details we wanted to include in our design.
Any Problems: Parts of our original design did not work because we did not think about some of the mechanical parts that were needed for the object to be used by the keepers.
Improvements: Overall, it went very well. I think this class could benefit from having two professors or a TA/GA/dedicated person to help in the lab so time can be used more effectively and Rob is not spread so thin.
Advice: Do more research about the birds, ask the keepers more questions about how the birds interact with each other socially.
Feedback: I'm so glad I took this class.

Object Description: A feeder meant to stretch the giraffes tongue in order to get the food reward. The intended purpose is to reduce tongue play.
Challenging Part: Deciding on materials and cutting into the plastic was challenging because we had one chance to get the shapes right
Successful Part: I think the ideation process was very successful because my group was very open to changes and were set on making a safe object that did what the keepers told us needed to be done.
Any Problems: No problems but we changed designs to be safer for the giraffe’s jaws
Improvements: Have more cardboard ready for use and plan out measurements prior to construction
Advice: Start looking for objects like a soap drum but don’t look like one early ( I wish our object looked less like a soap drum but I know it does what is needed so it’s ok)
Feedback: I think my group size of 3 people for our object was perfect but other groups definitely needed more people. Also maybe have less objects being made and have the whole class focus on one or two super ambitious objects that document data and still do intended enrichment.

Object Description: We created a wooden pyramidal structure to engage the Komodo’s muscles during feedings. This enrichment object uses gravity and a tug-of-war style rope mechanic.
Challenging Part: As the Komodo is an incredibly large animal, scale became an issue during our design process. We had to consider the feasibility of transportation and construction of this object if it were to be used regularly by keepers.
Successful Part: Creating models, personal research, and speaking to the zoo keepers themselves for feedback were all essential to push the project beyond just the design phase
Any Problems: The sheer scale and weight of our object made the production a group effort at almost all times. Adapting to the available tools was also an added challenge.
Improvements: Have a better understanding of the steps and time needed to complete an object and rationalize if it is possible within the given schedule.
Advice: A project of this scale will take more time and effort than may be realistic during the allotted time. This will be a very fun and rewarding project, though, and you’ll learn a lot from it.
Feedback: Overall this class and project were very challenging but such a fun process. I enjoyed working with teammates to brainstorm and push through creative and logistic roadblocks, and I would happily do it again. Going to the zoo and seeing the animals was also super cool. One thing I do recommend is maybe going to the zoo a bit sooner, I didn’t feel that the ball got rolling until our first visit where we could really visualize the object in the space and how the animals might interact with it.

Object Description: Our project was to address giraffes and how to engage their tongue since they were having problems with excessive tongue play. We made a feeder that engaged the tongue.
Challenging Part: Probably narrowing down one idea because there were a lot of interesting ones. Another was making sure we found an idea that could be created that would be safe for the animal.
Successful Part: Probably the use of materials we decided on and the pattern were most successful. We found safe and easily obtainable materials. Our design process was clear and we executed it effectively.
Any Problems: It was hard to create a good prototype because we didn’t have access to any of the actual materials we wanted to use and making it on a small scale with the real materials would have been pretty complicated.
Improvements: Spend a little less time prototyping and a bit more on the making because there will be unexpected problems. At least that’s what I saw from other groups. Our project was very organized we kept a good schedule and our project was appropriate to the amount of time we had.
Advice: I would tell myself that creating a date by date plan might be helpful, of course it can change, but conceptualizing when things need to get done would be helpful.
Feedback: This was a great project. I loved working on something meaningful and with other people!

Object Description: My group designed a naturalistic foraging log toy for the shore and shallows of the emerald forest aviary. This object is made of interlocking PVC components, consisting primarily of an internal tube with holes to dispense food that rolls around inside of a larger log with larger holes.
Challenging Part: The most challenging part of the design process was trying to anticipate challenges that might arise when working with unfamiliar materials.
Successful Part: I believe that doing several group brainstorming rounds, narrowing down many ideas into a few, and reiterating on cardboard models together contributed to the success of my group.
Any Problems:
I think our largest obstacles were as follows:
1. overestimating the weight of our materials, which we had hoped would float during our ideation.
2. surfacing our exterior log with wood stain before learning that oil based surfaces would reject the tarbender liquid epoxy. We lost some time working with mineral spirits and steel brushes to strip the stain away before resurfacing with acrylic paint.
Improvements: At times our group felt stuck in the modeling phase and I believe we spent more time working with cardboard than necessary. I think we might have benefitted from expediting the modeling phase, or perhaps focusing our attention less on appearance and more on the practical aspects of our project such as locking mechanisms, criteria for floating, etc.
Advice: If I could go back in time, I would have liked to stress to myself to look ahead as much as possible and begin demoing sculpting, drilling, and surfacing techniques much sooner.
Feedback: Thank you for this wonderful opportunity! This collaboration was a valuable chance to get hands on experience with material construction and enrichment design for zoos, a field I am immensely interested in.
